text: This was, without exaggeration, the WORST space movie in 20 years.  Absolutely idiotic, and even M. Night Shyamalon would think the "plot twist" at the end was absurd given the scenes that happen right up to it.  Granted, you could kind of tell how dumb the movie would be, to an extent, in the trailer, when they are catching the fast-moving space probe with the robot arm.  But it is gratifying to watch some of the bad actors die off at least.   I know they wanted to be a different kind of space movie, than _The Martian_, etc, and they succeeded -- since those other films were actually good.  They clearly wanted to be an _Alien(s)_ reimagining, but did not succeed.  Not that people will take this movie seriously, but it's also a dumb idea to scare people about the prospects of missions to Mars.

text: ****SPOILER ALERT***** ****SPOILER ALERT***** this movie was frustrating throughout and didn't make a lot of sense in terms of plot. First off, you would think a team that was chosen to go to space to encounter alien life would be at the very least decently smart, but each of them somehow make completely dumb and emotionally driven decisions that ultimately puts them in a shittier situation. Second of all, when Earth sent a capsule to push them into deeper space as a fail-safe move, how is it that only Miranda would know? Why didn't she tell everyone else before hand? Shouldn't there be some sort of procedure so EVERYONE will be aware of what will be happening, instead of having team members guess and possibly make the wrong choice, like Sho did, and blow off the frigging capsule and put the whole shuttle in orbit? You would think that such a HUGE decision like this would be really planned out before hand so no one will do anything stupid. This movie is dumb and every character in it is pretty darn dumb also.

You don't even have any evidence that there was ever ANY lifeform other than that one!!    "If we let it get to Earth, we'll risk all human life. Let's kill the thing!" WTF? Are you scientist or a bunch or dumb teenagers from a guetto in Chicago? You have in front of you the most revolutionary discovery of all history... and you are thinking of killing it? This cannot get more retarted, Jesus Christ. No one says you shouldn't take precautions of course, but "that thing" as you call it is the promise of the greatest and biggest change scientifically and phiosophically for all mankind. Bigger than you. Kiling it instead of using the infinite opportunities that would bring us to study it... makes no sense.

text: Anyone notice in all these kinds of space based movies, its either an asian/indian that's telling the crew he has a new kid back on earth? haha And as for all the horror and insanity that happened in this movie? There were dozens of opportunities for things to stop escalating. DOZENS. If anything, they each, the crew members, are guilty of helping things escalate, even past what they should have gotten to, without their help. It's hilarious. Not only did the majority of what I can imagine, protocols which we have in space for this situation, get ignored, but even common sense and individual intelligence was shattered, and completely lacking... and for people who are supposed to be super smart and capable of thinking outside the box, they weren't even able to think the few times they needed to, about them being inside a giant box floating in space, and how to fix the situation.   I get it, had it not been for each of those mistakes, it would have been a really short and boring movie. I get it, it's a movie. But the writers these days have gotten lazier then usual, or just uncreative, since its up to them to make it believable, or at least somewhat believable, no matter how insane the situation/horror is in that moment...
